"Bednarska A., Łoś J., Dawidowicz P.","Temperature-dependent effect of filamentous cyanobacteria on daphnia magna life history traits",2011,"Journal of Limnology","70","2",,"353","358",,,10.3274/JL11-70-2-19,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79959416186&partnerID=40&md5=749c5af36fdb767d1ed951cd72321253","Department of Hydrobiology, Faculty of Biology, University of Warsaw, Banacha 2, 02-097 Warsaw, Poland","Bednarska, A., Department of Hydrobiology, Faculty of Biology, University of Warsaw, Banacha 2, 02-097 Warsaw, Poland; Łoś, J., Department of Hydrobiology, Faculty of Biology, University of Warsaw, Banacha 2, 02-097 Warsaw, Poland; Dawidowicz, P., Department of Hydrobiology, Faculty of Biology, University of Warsaw, Banacha 2, 02-097 Warsaw, Poland","Filamentous cyanobacteria are unsuitable food for Daphnia due to their poor manageability, poor nutritional value and, in some cases, toxicity. As the strength of harmful effects of cyanobacteria on filter-feeding zooplankton is temperature dependent, the global warming scenarios for eutrophic lakes in temperate zone might include an escalated suppression of Daphnia populations caused by the presence of cyanobacterial filaments. To test this assumption, we conducted life-table experiments with four clones of Daphnia magna fed either a green alga Scenedesmus obliquus or a non-toxic strain of filamentous cyanobacteria Cylindrospermopsis raciborskii in two temperatures (20 °C and 24 °C). Key life history parameters of Daphnia, i.e., age and size at first reproduction, fecundity, and individual growth rate, were measured. Both food and temperature significantly affected Daphnia performance, however, the effect of interaction of these two factors was ambiguous and highly genotype-dependent. We conclude that the temperature increase within the studied range will not necessarily strengthen the suppression of Daphnia growth by filamentous cyanobacteria, but may affect clonal selection within population of Daphnia, thus possibly triggering microevolutionary changes within affected populations.","Global warming; Inter-clonal differences; Life history; Non toxic cyanobacteria","crustacean; cyanobacterium; environmental factor; eutrophic environment; evolutionary theory; fecundity; green alga; life history; temperature effect; zooplankton; Chlorophyta; Cyanobacteria; Cylindrospermopsis; Cylindrospermopsis raciborskii; Daphnia; Daphnia magna; Scenedesmus; Scenedesmus obliquus",,,,,,"Abrusán, G., Filamentous cyanobacteria, temperature and Daphnia growth: The role of fluid mechanics (2004) Oecologia, 141, pp. 395-401; Bednarska, A., Dawidowicz, P., Change in filterscreen morphology and depth selection: Uncoupled responses of Daphnia to the presence of filamentous cyanobacteria (2007) Limnol. Oceanogr, 52, pp. 2358-2363; Berthon, J.L., Brousse, S., Modification of migratory behavior of planktonic Crustacea in the presence of a bloom of Microcystis aeruginosa (Cyanobacteria) (1995) Hydrobiologia, 300-301, pp. 185-193; Briand, J.-F., Leboulanger, C., Humbert, J.-F., Bernard, C., Dufour, P., Cylindrospermopsis raciborskii (Cyanobacteria) invasion at mid-latitudes: Selection, wide physiological tolerance, or global warming (2004) J. Phycol, 40, pp. 231-238; Claska, M.E., The effect of temperature on the response of Daphnia to toxic cyanobacterium (1998) Freshwat. Biol, 39, pp. 221-232; Debernardi, R., Giussani, G., Are blue-green algae a suitable food for zooplankton? An Overview (1990) Hydrobiologia, 200-201, pp. 29-41; Demott, W.R., Foraging strategies and growth inhibition in five daphnids feeding on mixtures of a toxic cyanobacterium and a green alga (1999) Freshwat. Biol, 42, pp. 263-274; Forsyth, D.J., James, M.R., Cryer, M., Alteration of seasonal and diel patterns in vertical migration of zooplankton by Anabaena and planktivorous fish (1990) Arch. Hydrobiol, 117, pp. 385-404; Gliwicz, Z.M., Siedlar, E., Food size limitation and algae interfering with food collection in Da